(102, 1, '2018-02-18 16:53:25', '2018-02-18 16:53:25', '<div class="excerpt">\r\n\r\n#1: you don\'t have to know how to code. But wait! Donâ€™t dismiss your idea purely because you donâ€™t have any development experience â€“ not every tech start-up founder can code, and thatâ€™s okay.\r\n\r\nTake Airbnb, for example. Today itâ€™s a billion-dollar company, but neither of its founders had programming experience when they originally came up with the concept. From product validation to market fit and customer engagement, thereâ€™s plenty for a self-confessed ideas person or designer to do. So if you think you could be sitting on the next Snapchat but donâ€™t know what launching an app might involve, read on.\r\n\r\n</div>\r\n<section class="entry-content cf">\r\n<h2>1) You can outsource the techy bits</h2>\r\nAs weâ€™ve already established, the ability to code isnâ€™t necessarily a dealbreaker. However, you could make life a lot easier for yourself by saddling up with a technical co-founder. But if youâ€™re hellbent on keeping all the glory (and work) for yourself, you will need to enlist the services of a developer, so ask around for some recommendations. For <a href="http://www.cinderly.com/">Cinderly</a> co-founders Luke Stoffel and Laura von Holt â€“ neither of whom have programming experience â€“ they knew immediately that they wanted Australian developer David McKinney (the brains behind Emoji Type) to build their app, which helps users filter fashion finds, has been billed as the first data-driven style app of its kind. â€œDavid was twice our budget, but like all internet love stories, we figured it out,â€ says Laura.\r\n<h3><strong>2) Someoneâ€™s probably already thought of it</strong></h3>\r\nThere are currently over two million apps available on the App Store, so the chances of you coming up with an entirely new concept isnâ€™t all that likely. But fret not, boasting strong similarities to another app doesnâ€™t mean you have to go back to the drawing board. Ultimately, it all comes down to the execution. What if Facebook had bowed out before it had even begun because MySpace was already on the scene? If you think thereâ€™s a way to make it better, go forth and build. Or, you know, pay someone else to build.\r\n<h4><strong>3) Establish who your app caters to</strong></h4>\r\nApps can beÂ divided into three groups: apps that are born out of need, apps that generally make life easier and apps that are purely there for entertainment.\r\n\r\nâ€œReally think through the whole app from your userâ€™s point of view,â€ advises Laura. â€œWhat will it be like for them to use it, and where in their life do you fit in? For us, we realised it was a viable idea based on our own experiences of shopping in stores and online,â€ she says of the moment that she knew Cinderly had the potential to make the sometimes-arduous process of finding beautiful clothes that fit well easier.\r\n<h5><strong>4) There will be a <em>lot</em> of testing involved</strong></h5>\r\nAnd retesting. And possibly some more retesting. <a href="http://www.cinderly.com/">Cinderly</a> rolled out a soft launch around six months ago and has since been gathering information and feedback from users. TheÂ makers are currently in the process of refining the app before rolling out a new updated version in 2017. â€œWe want to make Cinderly like the Pokemon Go of retail â€“ a â€˜Mall Madnessâ€™ game for the digital age,â€ says Laura.\r\n<h6><strong>5) It might not work out</strong></h6>\r\nBefore you throw all of your energy into your app, you need to acknowledge that it mightnâ€™t be the resounding success that you dream it could be. If itâ€™s not, you wouldnâ€™t be alone. In fact, statistics show that as few as 11% of all apps created sell over the elusive 50,000 mark. And yet, if you really believe in your idea and are willing to be brave, put in the groundwork â€“ who knows where it could lead?\r\n\r\nLike the eye of a tornado, weâ€™re living slap-bang in the middle of the â€˜Thereâ€™s an app for thatâ€™ age. So if you havenâ€™t already flirted with the idea of launching your own app, youâ€™ve almost certainly had a fleeting idea for one before (probably) tossing it into the â€˜too hardâ€™ basket.\r\n\r\n</section>', '5 things you should know before launching your own app', 'Vestibulum vel aliquam nisl. Integer dignissim lorem vitae ligula tincidunt, nec sollicitudin magna suscipit. Sed tempor vulputate ornare. Duis quis sagittis dolor, id imperdiet lacus. Phasellus tincidunt ipsum augue.', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '23-revision-v1', '', '', '2018-02-18 16:53:25', '2018-02-18 16:53:25', '', 23, 'http://localhost:8888/23-revision-v1/', 0, 'revision', '', 0);
